  "topic_name": "Electricity",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Electric current is the flow of electric charges (electrons) through a conductor. For current to flow, a complete (closed) circuit is needed. A circuit consists of components like cell/battery (source), wires (conductors), switch (control), and load (like bulb). Conductors allow current to flow (metals like copper, aluminium), while insulators resist current flow (rubber, plastic, wood). Electric current has three main effects: heating effect (heater, bulb), magnetic effect (electromagnet), and chemical effect (electroplating). Standard symbols are used to draw circuit diagrams.",
    "rules": [
      "Electric current: flow of electric charges.",
      "Current flows from positive to negative terminal.",
      "A closed circuit is needed for current flow.",
      "Conductors allow current flow; insulators resist it.",
      "Heating effect: current produces heat in conductors.",
      "Magnetic effect: current creates magnetic field.",
      "Chemical effect: current causes chemical reactions.",
      "Open circuit: no current flows; closed circuit: current flows."
    ]
  },
